### Abstraction

Abstraction hides complex implementation details and exposes only essential features to the user. In C++, abstraction is achieved through abstract classes and interfaces.

---

### Abstract Classes

A class containing at least one pure virtual function is abstract:

```cpp
class Device {
public:
  virtual void turnOn() = 0;   // Pure virtual
  virtual void turnOff() = 0;  // Pure virtual
  virtual ~Device() {}
};
```

---

### Implementing Abstract Classes

```cpp
class TV : public Device {
public:
  void turnOn() override {
    cout << "TV is on";
  }
  void turnOff() override {
    cout << "TV is off";
  }
};
```

---

### Benefits of Abstraction

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Reduced complexity | User sees only relevant interface |
| Code reuse | Common interface for all implementations |
| Security | Hide sensitive implementation details |
| Flexibility | Change implementation without affecting users |

---

### Interface vs Abstract Class

| Aspect | Interface | Abstract Class |
|--------|-----------|---------------|
| Methods | All pure virtual | Can have concrete methods |
| Data members | Not allowed | Can have data members |
| Constructors | Not allowed | Can have constructors |
| C++ support | Use class with all pure virtual | Class with some pure virtual |

---

> **Key Point:** Abstraction focuses on what an object does, not how it does it. Use pure virtual functions to define interfaces in C++.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Database {
public:
  virtual void connect(string connStr) = 0;
  virtual void query(string sql) = 0;
  virtual void disconnect() = 0;
  virtual ~Database() {}
};

class MySQLDatabase : public Database {
public:
  void connect(string connStr) override {
    cout << "Connecting to MySQL: " << connStr << endl;
  }
  void query(string sql) override {
    cout << "MySQL query: " << sql << endl;
  }
  void disconnect() override {
    cout << "Disconnecting MySQL" << endl;
  }
};

int main() {
  Database* db = new MySQLDatabase();
  db->connect("localhost:3306");
  db->query("SELECT * FROM users");
  db->disconnect();
  delete db;
  return 0;
}
